text: That's the problem. Maleficent had no redeeming qualities whatsoever and is perhaps the one Disney villain not named Chernabog who was known to be pure evil. Maleficent is my favorite Disney villain for precisely that reason.   In this film notice how her curse now only puts Aurora to sleep instead of actually killing her. (Merryweather's gift was what reduced the curse to sleep.) Despite what we've seen in parts of these trailers, it's obvious that this film is trying to play down Maleficent's wickedness enough to actually make her seem redeemable. She's supposed to die by being stabbed in the heart during her faceoff with Charming; somehow I doubt that's going to happen here. What this movie is attempting to do is borderline character assassination.  Nevertheless, it looks cool and I'm sure I'll enjoy it if I overlook the original Sleeping Beauty film and Maleficent's portrayal in it. I'm expecting it to turn out sort of like Tim Burton's Alice in Wonderland. =/

text: This is what gets me...  There have been so many movies out recently where the villain HAS to be the tragic anti-hero that, in truth, is supposed to make us feel like she did nothing wrong. I was honestly expecting a turn-around with this where Maleficent is truly evil as can be, stealing the spotlight from every scene.  Now, from this trailer at least, we're getting some BS that Maleficent was actually "misunderstood" and that the King was the true evil! Oh lord... We do see her killing people in droves and sending in dragons (and not turning into one herself -_- ), but they still have the undertone of her being a fallen angel by someone else's evil. Why can't we just have a good Frollo villain again? I would love to see another Disney villain that takes evil to the next step.  Also, the CGI looks relatively poor. This is the same fantasy battle stuff used over and over in such terrible movies as Jack the Giant Slayer, Hanzel and Gretel, etc. Granted, the Lord of the Rings used CGI mixed with action, but then it was hard to tell what exactly was conventional effects and what was animation. Here, it all just looks really animated.  On that note... I feel less tempted to watch this. In the end I will probably go see it anyway, but now it just seems overly-pretentious. Maybe I might be wrong, but it's still too early to tell.

text: For those who keep on complaining about Maleficent's status as an antihero, let's get some things straight. In the original Disney movie, Maleficent was portrayed as evil because the movie was in the perspective of the three fairies. They saw Maleficent as a heartless monster and saw themselves as good parents for Aurora.   This movie, however, is in Maleficent's perspective where she sees herself as a misunderstood fairy trying to protect what is rightfully hers. Meanwhile, the three fairies are portrayed as "neglectful and superficial" towards Aurora.   Lastly, the movie changed the three fairies from the original movie because Maleficent never really knew that much about the fairies. Therefore, their names, appearance, and behavior had been changed for this movie.  (Sorry this message was so long).

text: I...am kinda torn between this movie.  On the one hand, I did not like the line "She shall fall into a lifelike sleep". In the original movie, it was Merryweather who lessened Maleficent's spell intended to kill the princesses into a sleep. That scene was Maleficent's establishing character moment. Not get invited to a party? Fucking murder the princess!  This change in that line together with other lines she tosses in the trailer makes me think this movie is going for a "tragic fallen heroine" like approach, like what Star Wars prequels did to Darth Vader with the difference that Vader at least had a redemeable moment in the originals when he killed the Emperor. But here... I mean, we are talking about Maleficent! No matter what Disney canon you are talking about whether the Disney's Channel "House of Mouse" show or Kingdom Hearts, she is always portrayed as the Mistress of All Evil. I will find it very hard to buy her gray morality attitude in this one.   And on the other hand, I am willing to give this movie a chance. Maybe this "not so evil" scenes are nothing but Maleficent being crafty and manipulative in which case, bravo Disney. I mean, at first I was very skeptical when I heard they casted Angelina Jolie, but watching the trailer now I think she did a spot on job (and appeared to had a blast doing so), so maybe the movies story will end up surprising me too.

text: The raven turning into a dragon is awesome, I wonder if they got the idea from Clara the dragon-turned-raven in the Fables comics? I'm not sure about having Maleficent deliberately softening her curse to a sleeping one, though maybe they just changed it for the trailer to prevent anyone getting confused over which fairytale they were re-telling (I agree it doesn't make much sense, but stranger advertising decisions have been made), or maybe they just didn't think they could make a sympathetic anti-villain who would deliberately pronounce death upon a child. At least Jolie does a decent voice, though there will never be an equal to Eleanor Audley. And they're STILL not letting us hear her laugh! Maybe they think half the potential viewers are only going to see the film to judge whether they get that iconic aspect right, and they'd lose customers if they cleared that up?

text: I wish people weren't so judgmental about Aurora's appearance. The animation version matured her way too much, she had an hourglass figure, a long face with sunken cheeks and arched eyebrows. This version portrays her as an adolescent and they got an actress of an appropriate age to play her. This movie will have lots of symbolism and I think one of those symbols is the contrast between beauty and disaster, youth and evil, sex and violence. Aurora is supposed to be someone who is extremely sheltered and innocent, which is why maleficent finds her and feeds her information about the world knowing there is an impending doom on the poor kid

text: Plot:  Maleficent, a beautiful pure-hearted young woman lives a idyllic life in a peaceful forest kingdom, until one day when an invading army threatenens the harmony of the land. Maleficent rises to become the land's fiercest protector, but she ultimately suffers a ruthless betrayal, an act that costs her wings and turns her pure heart to stone becoming "The Mistress of All Evil." Bent on revenge, Maleficent faces an epic battle with the invading King's successor and as a result, places a curse upon his newborn infant Aurora that upon her sixteenth birthday she shall prick her finger on the spindle of a spinning wheel and fall into a sleep like death.  Over the next sixteen years Maleficent comes across the young princess many times and comes to realise that Aurora may hold the key to peace in the kingdom and perhaps to Maleficent's true happiness as well. She befriends the princess in hopes of keeping her away from the curse she placed upon her.  (Source: Disney Wiki)

text: On one hand, it is another film trying to remake a Disney classic for the shake of modern audiences. Plus, it is very wrong to darken it up and drain it of color (minusing the three fairies). But, on the other hand, it looks like an amazingly great fantasy film. However, I have a problem... WHY IS NO ONE IN THE INDUSTRY MAKING ANIMATED FEATURES AS DARK AND EPIC AS THIS ANYMORE? 2D, 3D, or StopMo, it would be nice to see a modern animated feature without stupidity and pop-culture. I can say that I am glad that it (although seems weird) got a PG--Rating (my same hope for Star Wars VII)

text: Ok, I'm just trying to figure this out here. Maleficent is the top Disney villain of all time, did what she did because she wasn't invited to a damn party. That's not really something to get pissed off about to the point that you put a curse on the King & Queen's child.  But this film is trying to make Maleficent look like a good person, and that she knew Aurora? How will that work, that's like trying to make a Joker film, and make him look like a good person, despite all the crimes he committed. I'll check out this movie because of Angelina Jolie alone, in the trailers, she does a damn good job portraying the character Maleficent.   What's next, are going to get a live-action Snow White prequel about the evil Queen? This is not another version of sleeping beauty. this is a villain being ripped out from sleeping beauty and made her own film, just to show us how a villain became a villain and how human the feelings of a villain is.  NAH.. forget the hero's Journey, we want a villain's life misfortune and how he/she pull herself/himself out from misery. This is something we will learn in life guys, villaines are actually the one who teaches us not to turn like them or we'll suffer for our entire lives, not everything is a happy ending, everyone makes poor choices in life, not everyone are strong enough to battle against anger and revenge, and accept our imperfection and mistakes then forgive ourselves for that and the only person who can truly save us from such anger is ourselves.

text: !SPOILERS - SORTA!  this film is very very good - but they really coulda done with changing the name of the characters and doing away with the sleeping beauty script all together.  jolie is awesome in this... plays the role amazingly - especially when she makes the curse - thats when you believe she's maleficent... briefly... before going back into a character with a 3d complex that doesn't sit comfortable on an audience that already knows her as a villian...  my warning to you - if you go to the cinema expecting to be terrified of the evil and horrifying Maleficent, then you will leave disapointed.   But... if you come with an open mind - then you're in for a very good film.  In my personal opinion, i'd rather disney stick to the script - keep the maloficents evil and snow whites innocent, but thats my opinion - they turned a mouse into a household name, so what do i know.

text: I gotta say, this Maleficent film is everything I feared it would be, if not worse. They took her from a villain who was truly evil and embraced it and degraded into into an assembly-line "not evil, just misunderstood" anti-hero you see EVERYWHERE nowadays and I am SICK-TO-DEATH OF! It's a 'Wicked' rip-off at best. They just gave her the 'DracoInLeatherPants' treatment, while simultaneously giving Stefan and the Fairies the 'RonTheDeathEater' treatment. These tropes are ridiculed for a reason and their constant use in fanfiction; did the writers/directors really think making a movie with them as part of their main selection of tropes a great idea?

text: This movie was OK. There were a lot of problems with this film though. First, there was no point of the prince being in the story. His character had no crucial part in the story. Second (this is more of an acting part) The King. I've seen Sharlto Copley act as a villain, and this wasn't his best performance. Look at him in Elysium: Outstanding performance. In this movie, I wouldn't even call him "mad" and lastly, the message. Disney always has a great message in the end. In this one, well, there was none. Look at frozen, Wreck it Ralph, etc. They all have great messages about Family, love and friendship. Maleficent had none of it which greatly disappointed me. I wanted an ending that made me say: Wow, that's deep. But there was nothing. I expected something great from Maleficent, but there just wasn't anything. Just cliche moments, Lousy action, and major plot holes. The only good things in this film is the performance by Angelina Jolie, and the visual effects. Don't expect much humor, don't expect an ending that'll make you tear and don't expect the ending you read or saw before, cause this is not it.

text: The look is there...but the voice isn't!  I know I'm going to get kicked in the teeth for that statement, but let me follow it up by saying that I truly am looking forward to seeing this movie, and I have been since I first heard the rumors going around.    I had no doubts that Angelina had the look to pull this role off, but her soft voice was a bit of concern for me.  Out of all Disney's animated classics, "Sleeping Beauty" remains to be my favorite.  I have become so accustomed to the wonderfully theatrical, and "throaty" tone of Eleanor Audley's voice for Maleficent, that anything less - to me, would be unacceptable.  I have the same sentiment for Pat Carroll's Ursula from, "The Little Mermaid"  With a villain as evil as Maleficent, there needs to be just the right amount of depth and "threat" -- and maybe even a little "husk" to the voice to convince the audience that they are "not to be messed with".  When Walt was alive, he had such a knack for picking just the right voice for his villains - which is why Disney ALWAYS had the best villains, because a story is only as good as its villain, right?  Now, with all of that said, I will say that this doesn't change my wanting to see the film by any stretch of the imagine, because I know I'll love it regardless because Maleficent is one of the greatest villains of all time in my book, and I can't wait to see it.  ...and so, that's my two cents worth, lol.

text: Wow this movie was terrible. It felt like a 7 year old wrote the screenplay. Seriously, can people honestly say that this movie was a good idea? Nothing in the plot makes any sense; and don't try to say that it's because it is a kids movie. Kids movies may be fantastical, but the actions and motivations behind the characters tend to make logical sense to real people. Not in Maleficent, where people fall into betrayal "just cause why not". Fairy = good. Man = bad. Again, men come off as untrustworthy, power hungry snobs, so soon after "Frozen" just made the exact same point. I should point out that while man was the aggressor in the film (for no particular reason other than just because why not randomly attack some fairy folk), Maleficent is the only person in the movie to actually kill anyone. She murders like 30 dudes. The men try to kill fairies but never succeed. So she technically is the villain. But also the poor, poor, misunderstood good guy. Are all bad people actually just misunderstood heroes? That's what Disney wants us to believe. That's like saying Hitler was just misunderstood. This film is as feeble as all of the other attempts by Disney to ruin the it's classic animated franchise and turn them into regurgitated live-action plot-less garbage.

text: This movie has so many twists it makes Shyamalan cringe. They had a clear direction to take that would both make this a good movie, AND stay faithful to the original. Instead they pass on it by introducing yet another twist. Another note, what happened to Villains just being evil? Every villain nowadays are "misunderstood" or "heartbroken" or "messed up in the head." etc. Here's 2 newsflashes. 1. We all know this is a work of fiction, not everyone needs a psychological dissection. Have someone be evil just for the sake of being evil and no one will question why. Which brings me to the second newsflash, bad people just for the sake of being bad exist in the real world. Every villain we see nowadays are all tragedy. What happened to good old days where villains were just assholes and heroes were tragic? This movie upset me, as you can tell.

text: I was disappointed with my reaction at the end of the movie. I was hoping to be blown away. All I could say was "It was okay" idk it felt like something was missing, but I can't figure out what it is. The story felt rushed, not done that well. I'm really hoping Cinemasins will go over this movie once it's released. A few of the "movie sins" were just too obvious. I was kinda mad that Maleficent's character didn;t even turn full on evil after her wings were stolen. During the animated film when she sets her curse into motion, at the end she says that Aurora will prick her finger "AND DIE!" I was waiting for that epic part T^T But it didn't happen. Instead I get this "dead sleep, true kiss" nonsense. You know what else didn't happen? The 3rd fairy never gave Aurora her gift. Because her gift was that she wouldn't die. but only be asleep until true loves first kiss. This means that the fairies giving Aurora "gifts" were pointless. WTF? I had no problem with Maleficent being the hero and villain,but she wasn't even a villain!!! I have no idea why this happened in the movie. There was just nothing spectacular about the movie besides the visuals. Which was fan-fuckin-tastic!

text: I was really disappointed by this ending, it was too happy. I felt Maleficent should have been the unsung misunderstood Hero who dies......       ...... Instead of waking Aurora and killing the King and then all ends happily ever after. You just saw te king die and then you see aurora crowned. You barely saw what life in the human world is like to compare. I guess it's assumed but you barely see any common folk life except for the maids cleaning, doing laundry, spinning in spindles. The movie was still beautiful. I fell in love with the creatures! text: I did not like this movie, and probably I will never know why did people like it. My question, what was the purpose of this movie? What did it want to be? What did it want to tell?  So, you mean to tell me, this is a good fairy, the protector of the Moors, a nice girl/woman, and a misunderstood character who is actually not evil and such things, but she has a demon's wings and horns, and to put the cherry on the cake, her name is Maleficent?! Who would trust anyone who has evil looks and an evil name? If she has been that since they-don't-explain-when, she should be misunderstood from the beginning. What is next? Some little cute innocent looking-girl whose name is "The Backstabbing Satanic Gore-Loving Little Rapist and Homicidal Psychopath"?  I presume that you wanted to see the Sleeping Beauty from Maleficent's point of view. Maleficent razing kingdoms to the ground, transforming into a dragon (a dragon like Smaug from The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug. It doesn't matter what you think of that movie, that dragon's voice and looks were impressive), doing evil things for fun... this movie is not that. It is like an altered, twisted and totally changed version of Disney's The Sleeping Beauty (I put Disney's because I know there are more versions), and I give credit for some characters having PERSONALITIES (especially Maleficent, even if I did not like her story here), but Phillip... even a stone has more personality than him in this film.  There are characters that you do not know if they are good or evil until the end (Like Snape or Itachi Uchiha) but here it did not work. THIS made me hard to take the movie seriously.  Maleficent secretly raises and saves Aurora's life in multiple occasions, so she would fall in an eternal sleep or die when she became 16 so she has her revenge on her ex-boyfriend. Does anybody think this makes sense? Sparing someone to kill her?  This movie had potential, but most of it was wasted. If it was the biography of Maleficent while being loyal to the 1959 version (her being killed by Phillip rather than remaining alive for example, and regardless of them making her a villain like in the 1959 movie or an anti-hero or misunderstood character), better writing and less CGI this would be a stronger movie.  The positive things about this movie are that the visual effects for the Moors were beautiful (but its creatures were terrible. Seriously Hollywood, stop abusing the CGI, even Roger Rabbit's cartoons were more believable than that), the actors were very good (but Stephan had a funny accent), and the fights and background music were very, very good.  My score is 50/100.  My biggest fear with this movie is that new generations will see Maleficent as good, or evil-looking good, instead of the charismatic yet poor in personality version of 1959.   *SPOILER ALERT*  The solution to Aurora's eternal sleeping was recycled from Frozen. I hope the next time that can be solved like that they are more specific in what kind of love they mean (eros, philia, storge, agape).

text: Honestly, I really enjoyed Maleficent. I can say without a doubt that it was not the best film - or even the best story - ever, but I still found it interesting and entertaining and would definitely see it again.  The *only* problem I have a problem with when it comes to those who feel the opposite, however, is that so many keep saying that it was not true to the original story, or were under the impression it was a remake of Sleeping Beauty. a) It's called *Maleficent* for a reason. and more importantly... b) Pretty much the first line of the film is the narrator outright stating that the film is *a retelling of an old classic* - a *reinterpretation*. If you came out of that cinema angry about lack of faith to the original after hearing that within the first sixty seconds of the film, you're just an idiot.  It's fine if you don't like it, not everybody likes everything, but at least get your facts straight before beginning to criticise it.

text: At first I thought I'd be mad they changed the story so much but in reality they didn't.  The people who told the original "Sleeping Beauty" changed it, as people can twist stories and keep most of the elements but not tell the whole truth.  Keep in mind that the whole point was that the original story was history re-written by a man to make the king (and prince for that matter) look like the hero.  Many stories in real life are this way, so they are showing how it became ever so twisted enough by those who told it to change the empathy.  This, as told by an elderly Aurora, is actually more believable, as no one would curse a baby simply for not getting an invitation.  And the scene of her waking without wings was like being drugged and violated, like date rape.  We are told the TRUTH here (much like people who who were first taught that Christopher Columbus as a great hero and that gorillas were violent and vicious).  We were lied to as kids.

text: Disney miss out on the point they are trying to make.  They want to give Maleficent redemption, but there are too many problems. The plot is too undeveloped, they just switch character traits to make Maleficent protagonist and king stefan a bad guy, then they throw in a One Direction look alike to play the prince.  Giving Maleficent a tragic love story is the easiest way for people to relate to her and make her evilness understandable. If Disney want to be mainstream fine but they dont have to act like this is a big move towards a bigger understanding of the many nuances of morality.  The movie basicaly consist of a good idea, but it is to undeveloped, I dont know if Disney didnt have the time but they certainly have the resources and if they spent a little less on the CGI and a litle more on the characters and the plot it could have been much better.

text: If you seen Maleficent .. these are a couple of scenes that didn't make it into the movie because Disney felt they were "too dark" ..    1) The original story began when Maleficent's parents were killed in a war with the humans and it had a serious trauma on Maleficent as wel as trust issues. 2) Not only did King Stefan take her wings, he drugged Maleficent and raped her afterwards  3) When King Stefan presents the wings to the dying king, the dying king laughs him off saying he is just a servant, at this, King Stefan becomes very angry, grabs a pillow and kills him and calls himself "the new king" 4) In the original movie, they decided to turn Maleficent into a dragon and have the typicall Sleeping Beauty ending where she dies at the end, however they changed it so that Stefan died and Maleficent lived, they had to shot new scenes for this.  5) In the beginning she speaks to her raven of an missunderstood Queen who was tricked by a mirror thinking she was ugly, referring to The Evil Queen of Snow White, saying that these take place in the same universe.

text: Mis cómplices, Maléfica, es la historia de una hermosa joven de gran corazón, crece idílicamente en el pacífico reino del bosque, hasta que un día un ejército invasor de seres humanos amenaza la armonía del lugar. Maléfica se convierte en una feroz protectora de su tierra pero, al sufrir una despiadada traición, su noble corazón de a poco se vuelve de piedra. Decidida a vengarse, Maléfica se enfrenta en una batalla épica con el rey de los humanos y, como resultado, lanza una maldición sobre su hija recién nacida, Aurora. A medida que la niña crece, Maléfica descubre que Aurora no sólo es la clave para lograr la paz en el reino, sino también para recuperar su verdadera felicidad. No se la pierdan!!

text: I don't like this movie, but not for the reasons everyone else is saying. Why did they have to take the most wonderfully evil characters in Disney history, and make her good? The woman who's name literally means evil. I was hopping this movie would make the 'bad guys' and the 'good guys' of the classic seem more morally ambiguous. You know, to hammer the point home for the little kiddies that no one is completely good or evil, but, nope, they just made her the complete good guy. We've seen shows like Breaking Bad, Game of Thrones and countless other books and movies tell this tale before, so why not a Disney movie? The only reason I can think of is that they don't want to hurt the little kids' minds by making them think and ask, "Why?" and that just disappoints me.

text: Honestly, this movie is so emotional in presenting the audience the message between the relationship of father and daughter, also with her father's love and nemesis (Maleficent). Angelina Jolie's acting was exquisitely displayed in such a brave and vigorous manner, while the director actually presented good camera shots AND a tremendous happy ending in contrast to the 1959 film 'Sleeping Beauty'. But what really positions us, the audience, about this film is that we should cooperate with the villains. We should love them, in any way, just what a Christian is taught *not racial*. And so, with Aurora thanking Maleficent for raising her, the ending is the one I'm thinking of that leaves us in tears in terms of happiness.  P.S. I forgot to mention, but King David used to be Maleficent's true love at the start. Sad that he changed roles from being Maleficent's lover to her enemy.
